<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 26 日星期三 02:14:35 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. Woos Pacific Nation Where China Has Stamped Its Mark]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>国务卿安东尼·布林肯在汤加遭受火山爆发和海啸破坏后访问该国<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001084588"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823851?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">去年一月，汤加主岛上的海滩度假村因火山喷发而被毁。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：mary lyn fonua/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001084588"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/vivian-salama" itemprop="url" rel="author">维维安·萨拉马</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 25 日晚上 7:52 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-woos-pacific-nation-where-china-has-stamped-its-mark-913e29cb"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>汤加努库阿洛法——去年，当洪加汤加-洪加哈派<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tonga-cut-off-after-volcanic-eruption-tsunami-11642296898?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">火山爆发</a>， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tonga-left-largely-cut-off-after-volcanic-eruption-tsunami-11642405227" target="_blank" class="icon none">给这个南太平洋小岛带来毁灭时</a>，美国竞相提供急需的人道主义援助。中国也是如此。</p><p>火山爆发后引发了 50 英尺高的海啸，摧毁了距离新西兰海岸约 1,000 英里的群岛上的许多房屋。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-spacex-seeks-to-reconnect-tonga-to-internet-11644410232" target="_blank" class="icon none">海底电缆被毁</a>，居民只能拨打国内电话。柴油很快就变得稀少， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-volcano-eruption-spewed-ash-tonga-needs-rain-and-more-brooms-11643200347" target="_blank" class="icon none">干净的饮用水</a>几乎不可能找到。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-volcano-eruption-tonga-needs-to-bring-in-aid-but-keep-out-covid-19-11642495532?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">灾难发生后</a>，美国国际开发署提供了260万美元的人道主义援助来支持汤加人民，美国官员表示，这表明了华盛顿对具有重要战略意义的太平洋岛屿的承诺。周三，国务卿安东尼·布林肯是第一位访问汤加的美国内阁成员，他在汤加为新开设的美国大使馆举行了落成典礼，并与南太平洋最后一个波利尼西亚王国的领导人进行了讨论。</p><p>美国一直在寻求加强其在太平洋地区的影响力，以对抗中国日益增长的影响力。布林肯三年内三次访问太平洋岛屿，周三的访问将是他第12次访问印度-太平洋地区。尽管如此，一些太平洋领导人仍认为，在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-urged-to-step-up-in-the-pacific-after-chinas-whirlwind-trip-11654433738?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国多年来与中国的接触乏善可陈、</a>使中国在该地区获得影响力之后，拜登政府正在迎头赶上。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823853?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">安东尼·布林肯三​​年内三次访问太平洋岛屿。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安娜·钱梅梅克/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国越来越迫切地意识到需要迅速建立更紧密的联盟，特别是在中国去年与附近的所罗门群岛<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/solomon-islands-ties-with-china-challenge-western-dominance-of-pacific-11648216871?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">达成安全协议</a>之后。</p><p>在汤加主岛上，中国的足迹清晰可见，许多店面和商用车辆都贴有中文标志。布林肯周三与汤加总理一起举行新闻发布会的政府主楼由上海建工集团于 2015 年竣工，并获得中国 1100 万美元的资助。</p><p>布林肯表示：“我们不反对包括中国在内的任何其他国家的投资或参与。” “如果它以富有成效的方式完成，如果它确实满足了人们的需求……那是一件好事。”</p><p>去年自然灾害发生后，中国派出解放军飞机和军舰向汤加提供了10万美元的紧急援助，包括饮用水和食品，并承诺定期提供援助，满足汤加的长期需求。</p><p>中国的救援力量包括解放军南部战区司令部的海军和空军营，包括运20运输机和两艘军舰——这艘军舰主要部署于两栖登陆任务，但也可以执行人道主义援助和平民疏散任务，以及901型快速战斗支援舰旨在支持航母编队，凸显了解放军对开展非军事行动的兴趣。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="396" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823858?width=700&amp;height=396" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2019 年，一家中国投资银行在汤加的开发项目。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马克·贝克/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>中国外交部援引汤加副首相波阿西·泰的话称，汤加政府称赞北京是“真正的朋友”。</p><p>去年，拜登政府邀请十多个太平洋小岛屿国家的领导人前往华盛顿， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/small-pacific-islands-leaders-wooed-with-white-house-summit-assistance-11664474188?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">举办了为期两天的聚会</a>，以强调美国对该地区的承诺，该地区目前正与中国竞争。虽然许多岛屿面积和人口都很小，但它们横跨<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-fishing-fleet-the-worlds-largest-drives-beijings-global-ambitions-11619015507?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">广阔的水道，</a>对商业航运、渔业和安全具有战略意义。</p><p>一位美国高级官员表示，汤加与其他太平洋国家一样，对深化美国在气候变化、公共卫生和基础设施投资方面的承诺非常感兴趣。</p><p>安全专家表示，进入一些战略岛屿可能会让中国限制澳大利亚，并阻止美国军队大规模干预<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-warns-taiwan-with-an-eye-on-rest-of-the-world-cea19bf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对台湾或菲律宾等盟国的袭击</a>。</p><p>因此，美国在该地区的盟友也意识到加强其在大洋洲影响力的紧迫性。去年10月，南太平洋各国国防部长在汤加会面，有意建立更紧密的军事关系，以取代中国。汤加是仅有的三个拥有军队的太平洋岛国之一，其中包括巴布亚新几内亚和斐济。新西兰、法国、澳大利亚和智利也参加了会议。</p><p>汤加过去曾利用其军队为国际和平与安全任务做出贡献，包括前往伊拉克和阿富汗的任务。本月，汤加军队正在澳大利亚参加<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-allies-hold-record-setting-military-exercise-in-australia-in-message-aimed-at-china-86080059?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">由美国及其盟国参加的两年一度的训练演习</a>。 2014年，内华达州国民警卫队还与汤加签订了国家伙伴关系计划。现在，美国希望汤加能够利用其军队在离本土更近的地方执行互利任务。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823857?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">去年1月，斐济的一个港口看到一批从中国运往汤加的紧急援助物资。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：张永兴/新华社/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“我们希望实地改善与汤加人民的接触、沟通渠道和文化联系；探索我们可以深化合作的方式，”一位国务院高级官员表示。 “汤加是太平洋地区拥有军队的三个国家之一，因此军民合作非常重要，并且肯定会继续下去。”</p><p>这位官员否认五月份正式启用的美国驻汤加新大使馆旨在对抗中国的影响力，但承认太平洋地区的竞争是一个持续存在的现实。一些专家表示，汤加可能是一个有用的试金石，可以检验美国的应对措施相对于中国的长期承诺是否达到目标。</p><p>汤加长期以来一直要求美国在该国设立领事服务，以帮助那些希望访问的人办理签证，特别是因为约 60% 的汤加人属于摩门教，而且许多人有亲戚居住在美国</p><p>美国和平研究所高级专家布莱恩·哈丁表示：“如果美国要认真参与该地区的事务，就需要打好基础，首先要在更多国家设立大使馆。” “布林肯此行强调的就是这方面的进展。”</p><p>布林肯计划在汤加停留后前往新西兰和澳大利亚。在新西兰惠灵顿，他将与该国领导人举行会议，然后观看美国女足在世界杯上对阵荷兰队的比赛。</p><p>在澳大利亚布里斯班，他预计将与国防部长劳埃德·奥斯汀、澳大利亚副总理兼国防部长理查德·马勒斯和澳大利亚外交部长黄英贤一起参加一年一度的澳大利亚-美国部长级磋商（Ausmin）。</p><p>美国、澳大利亚和英国于 2021 年达成了一项<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-the-u-s-agreed-to-provide-nuclear-sub-technology-to-australia-2b631d8f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">名为“Aukus”的</a>协议，以增强三个国家在印太地区的集体威慑力。</p><p>写信给 Vivian Salama： <a href="mailto:vivian.salama@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">vivian.salama@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 23:52:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-woos-pacific-nation-where-china-has-stamped-its-mark-913e29cb</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-woos-pacific-nation-where-china-has-stamped-its-mark-913e29cb<author><![CDATA[Vivian Salama]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>发展/人道主义援助</category><category>国际关系</category><category>灾害/事故</category><category>地质灾害</category><category>洪水/海啸</category><category>自然灾害</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>海啸</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>安东尼·布林肯</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>发展</category><category>人道主义援助</category><category>国际关系</category><category>灾难</category><category>事故</category><category>地质灾害</category><category>洪水</category><category>潮汐波</category><category>自然灾害</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>海啸</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Eight Men Convicted in Brussels Bombings]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> 2016年恐怖袭击造成30多人死亡、数百人受伤<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001084176"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823795?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在布鲁塞尔恐怖袭击案审判开始时，安全人员监视被告坐在法庭内一个专门设计的玻璃盒子里。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：奥利维尔·马蒂斯/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001084176"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/laurence-norman" itemprop="url" rel="author">劳伦斯·诺曼</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/kim-mackrael" itemprop="url" rel="author">金·麦克雷尔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 25 日下午 6:22（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eight-men-convicted-in-brussels-bombings-f617b0df"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>布鲁塞尔——周二，8 名男子因参与 2016 年布鲁塞尔主要机场和地铁站发生的一系列爆炸袭击事件而被判有罪，该袭击事件造成 30 多人死亡、数百人受伤。</p><p>经过长达七个月的审判后作出了判决。预计量刑将于今年晚些时候进行。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/people-injured-after-explosion-at-brussels-airport-police-say-1458632527?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">伊斯兰国恐怖组织声称对</a>这两起恐怖袭击事件负责，这也是比利时和平时期历史上最致命的一次恐怖袭击发生在 2016 年 3 月 22 日上午。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>据比利时通讯社 Belga 报道，六名男子被判犯有恐怖分子谋杀罪。另外两人被判犯有恐怖组织成员罪，两人在北大西洋公约组织前总部举行的高度戒备审判中被无罪释放。</p><p>袭击当天，自杀式炸弹袭击者纳吉姆·拉奇拉维 (Najim Laachraoui) 和易卜拉欣·巴克拉维 (Ibrahim el-Bakraoui) 在该市国际机场引爆炸弹，造成 16 人死亡。大约一个小时后，巴克拉维的兄弟哈立德在布鲁塞尔地铁站引爆炸弹，造成另外 16 人死亡。</p><p>比利时当局逮捕了因 2015 年 11 月造成 130 人死亡的巴黎袭击事件而被通缉的穆罕默德·阿布里尼 (Mohamed Abrini)，并将他列为第三名机场炸弹袭击者，但他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brussels-attacks-could-have-been-much-worse-investigators-say-1463000343?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在未触发装置后逃跑</a>。</p><p>比利时当局指控奥萨马·克雷姆 (Osama Krayem) 涉嫌当天在地铁系统引爆另一枚炸弹，但未遂。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823797?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2016 年布鲁塞尔袭击当天，该市国际机场发生自杀式爆炸事件，造成 16 人死亡。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Laurent Dubrule/epa/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brussels-attacks-expose-europes-scant-progress-on-security-1458829690?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">布鲁塞尔袭击</a>发生在萨拉赫·阿卜杜斯拉姆在布鲁塞尔被捕四天后。他是实施巴黎大屠杀的十人袭击小组中唯一的幸存者。被捕后，该组织改变了在法国发动新袭击的计划，决定袭击比利时目标。</p><p>去年，法国一家法院对阿卜杜斯拉姆、阿布里尼和乌萨马·阿塔尔判刑，</p>据信他于 2017 年在叙利亚的一次空袭中丧生。<p></p><p>周二晚上无法立即联系到被定罪男子的律师。</p><p>周二被无罪释放的斯梅尔·法里西的律师表示，这一判决让他的当事人松了一口气。法比安·劳沃表示：“比利时的反恐司法已经证明是公平且审慎的。”</p><p>据 Belga 报道，在比利时审判期间，法院院长将布鲁塞尔袭击事件的官方死亡人数上调至 35 人，因为袭击发生后几年内已有 3 名受害者死亡。</p><p>遇难者包括一对美国夫妇以及来自印度、中国、秘鲁、德国、荷兰、英国、瑞典、刚果、意大利和比利时的其他人。</p><p>写信给劳伦斯·诺曼<a href="mailto:laurence.norman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(launce.norman@wsj.com)</a>和金·麦克雷尔 (Kim Mackrael) <a href="mailto:kim.mackrael@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">kim.mackrael@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 22:22:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/eight-men-convicted-in-brussels-bombings-f617b0df</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/eight-men-convicted-in-brussels-bombings-f617b0df<author><![CDATA[Laurence NormanKim Mackrael]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Israel in Political and Economic Tumult; Doctors Strike, Stocks Tumble]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>反对总理司法改革的抗议运动领导人发誓将继续反对立法<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081582"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisraeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列医生周二举行罢工，当局在因总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府进行的司法改革而发生骚乱的夜晚，强行将抗议者从道路上带走。照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081582"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">多夫·利伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 25 日下午 1:01（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>特拉维夫——总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡开始改革<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">司法系统</a>后，以色列人准备迎接新的政治和经济动荡时期，医生罢工，股市和货币下跌，抗议者发誓要继续大规模示威。</p><p>经过一晚的抗议活动后，以色列人等待周一通过的这项旨在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/netanyahu-revives-judicial-overhaul-stripped-of-most-controversial-piece-33160de?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">限制最高法院权力</a>并赋予立法者更多权力的立法的影响，全国局势紧张。已经向高等法院提交了请愿书，要求其废除该法律，此举可能引发宪法危机。他们还在观望，如果法案通过，数千名威胁将拒绝报到的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff" target="_blank" class="icon none">预备役军人</a>是否会信守诺言。他们目睹了经济似乎因<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71" target="_blank" class="icon none">政治戏剧</a>的上演而陷入短暂的冲击。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>该法律的通过标志着以色列社会的一个关键时刻，以色列社会分为两部分：一大部分是世俗以色列人，他们担心这项立法会破坏该国的自由民主；另一部分则是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-ultra-orthodox-haredim-military-service-supreme-court-of-ultra-orthodox-jews-shakes-israels-sense-of-identity-b3155e01?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">宗教和极端民族主义选民</a>，他们认为法院由自由派法官主导，而这些人经常推翻法院的判决。人民的意志。</p><p>以色列主要股市指数 TA-35 自周二开盘以来下跌超过 3%。过去一个月，以色列股市一直呈上升趋势，希望能够就立法达成妥协。周二，以色列货币谢克尔兑美元汇率下跌 1.3%。</p><p>以色列最大的投资公司之一梅塔夫投资公司(Meitav Investment House)的首席经济学家亚历克斯·扎贝任斯基(Alex Zabezhinsky)表示，谢克尔兑美元的价值在很大程度上反映了美国股市的情况，直到今年年初司法改革立法首次公布，此后一直如此。已断开连接。</p><p> “超过10%的贬值是政治骚乱的结果，”他说。他说，如果没有国内动荡，其价值应在 1 美元兑换 3.3 谢克尔左右。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MS" class="company-name">摩根士丹利</a>表示，将以色列的主权信用评级下调至“不喜欢的立场”。穆迪投资者服务公司表示，该法案的通过表明以色列的社会和政治紧张局势将持续“对以色列的经济和安全局势产生负面影响”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823386?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>内塔尼亚胡和财政部长贝扎雷尔·斯莫特里奇在一份联合声明中表示：“这只是暂时的反应，当尘埃落定后，就会清楚地看到以色列的经济非常强劲。”</p><p>两人指出了以色列日益增长的天然气工业、英特尔<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-netanyahu-touts-expanded-investment-by-intel-amid-tech-backlash-e0bdbfe6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最近向该国投资 250 亿美元</a>以及<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVDA" class="company-name">Nvidia</a>的选择</p>在以色列建造一台超级计算机等，作为以色列强劲经济的证据。<p></p><p>声明称：“以色列经济有着强劲的基本面，并将在经验丰富的领导层以及制定负责任的经济政策的领导下继续增长。”</p><p>四月份，穆迪警告说，政府的计划可能会损害该国的经济前景。该机构重申了以色列的 A1 评级，但将其前景从积极调整为稳定，这表明未来可能会下调该国的评级。</p><p>网络安全初创公司 AxoniusX 首席执行官阿米尔·奥菲克 (Amir Ofek) 表示：“很明显，投资者将会产生疑问和疑虑——当以色列的环境不再可预测时，为什么还要投资以色列。” “很明显，作为以色列人，我们只是在搬起石头砸自己的腿。”</p><p>代表高科技工人的抗议团体在五家主要报纸上刊登了全黑版的头版广告。另一边，广告上写着“以色列的引擎永远不会放弃”。以色列<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-startups-struggle-to-raise-money-amid-political-turmoil-global-downturn-52703ac1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">科技行业</a>一直处于反对该立法的最前线。许多科技工作者认为，此次改革将破坏民主和对该国法院系统的信心，这可能会吓跑投资者和人才。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823096?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名抗议者在耶路撒冷议会附近举行示威活动时举着以色列国旗。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“这很好地代表了我们的感受，”说</p>支付公司 Papaya Global 的首席执行官 Eynat Guez 拍摄了高科技工人拍摄的广告。盖兹表示，她希望市场反应和来自银行的负面情绪能够促使内塔尼亚胡和他的政党中的其他人“清醒过来……否则他们将作为毁灭以色列的人而被载入史册。”<p></p><p>以色列高度依赖其技术部门，该部门占该国国内生产总值的 15%，占出口额的一半左右。近几十年来，该国不断繁荣，吸引了外国投资，推动了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-boom-floods-israels-silicon-valley-with-cash-exposing-divisions-11632562536?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">初创企业和科技公司的爆炸式增长</a>。许多以色列科技公司的总部或员工都居住在特拉维夫地区，这是以色列世俗和自由派的基地，大规模示威活动已连续 29 周发生。</p><p> Bessemer Venture Partners 驻以色列合伙人 Adam Fisher 表示，该法案的通过不会对以色列科技公司产生明显而直接的影响，但会导致更多员工选择迁出以色列。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823452?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “这对国家来说是损失，但对以色列高科技来说不一定是损失，”他说。</p><p>周一通过的法案剥夺了最高法院撤销其认为“极其不合理”的政府决定的能力，这是法院用来确保政府在做出适当考虑的情况下做出决定的标准。这包括雇用和解雇重要的政府任命，例如政府部长、总检察长和安全部门负责人。</p><p>自该法案通过以来，已经向高等法院提交了几份请愿书，试图推翻该法案。尽管法院从未否决过像周一通过的法案这样的法案（相当于宪法修正案），但以色列宪法学者表示，法官们认为法院可以拥有这样的权力。</p><p>以色列国家安全部长伊塔马尔·本-格维尔表示，最高法院否决该法案的举动将被视为“未遂政变”。</p><p>以色列医学协会表示，之所以发起此次罢工，是因为新法律取消了对卫生部政治领导层的司法审查，称这将“对卫生系统、患者和医生造成严重后果”。该协会表示，它已游说政府继续对卫生系统进行司法审查。</p><p> “医疗系统是以色列许多其他地方所不存在的独特生态系统。它让不同部门的人们能够为了共同利益而和平合作，”38 岁的特拉维夫老年病学家亚伦·比莱克 (Aaron Bilek) 表示，他参加了罢工。 “感觉庇护所受到威胁真的很可怕。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Ari Flanzraich 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Dov Lieber，邮箱为<a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 17:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7<author><![CDATA[Dov Lieber]]></author><category>以色列</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Stuck on a Flight? Know Your Rights During a Tarmac Delay]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>如果恶劣天气或飞机拥堵导致您滞留在跑道上，以下是您作为航空公司乘客的权利<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821700/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>乔恩·克劳斯 (Jon Krause) 的插图<span>乔恩·克劳斯 (Jon Krause) 的插图</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073822"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073822"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/allison-pohle" itemprop="url" rel="author">艾莉森·波尔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 25 日中午 12:13（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tarmac-delay-rights-airports-9c5b1464"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>今年夏天，对于美国旅行者来说，计划外的停机坪时间变得令人沮丧地司空见惯。</p><p>有关停机坪延误的联邦数据滞后三个月，但经验丰富的旅客表示，他们观察到全国主要机场停机坪上的等待时间很长。在典型的停机坪延误中，飞机要么到达并需要等待登机口，要么在飞机舱门关闭后等待起飞。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/flight-cancellations-and-delays-mount-as-thunderstorms-hit-east-coast-c11c9161?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">恶劣的天气</a>给航空公司的运营带来了压力，并导致停机坪延误。天气问题导致飞机起飞延迟，并导致抵达飞机的可用登机口短缺。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/united-airlines-newark-flights-cut-9f5f57f6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">纽约地区机场的</a>延误情况非常明显。运营机场的纽约和新泽西港务局表示，当天气恶化时，出发和到达的时间会更加间隔。航空公司高管还表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/faa-tries-to-ease-flight-congestion-at-new-york-airports-933d1da0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，空中交通管制员的短缺</a>加剧了挑战。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “没有人对机场延误感到高兴，这就是为什么我们正在与合作伙伴密切合作，以减少停机坪延误，而停机坪延误很大程度上是由纽约/新泽西地区和目的地机场最近的恶劣天气造成的。”港务局发言人在一封电子邮件中说道。</p><p>十多年前，交通部实施了一项禁止停机坪长时间延误的规定。如果航空公司让乘客在飞机上停留的时间超过交通部规定的时间且没有机会下机，他们可能会面临罚款。航空分析师表示，这一规定大大减少了乘客在飞机上滞留数小时的事件数量。但航班延误仍然时有发生——交通部对停机坪延误的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/united-airlines-is-fined-1-9-million-for-runway-delays-11632516201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">航空公司处以罚款</a>，其中包括 2021 年对<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UAL" class="company-name">美国联合航空公司 (United Airlines)</a>的 190 万美元罚款。</p><p> 7月17日<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DAL" class="company-name">，达美航空一架</a>从拉斯维加斯飞往亚特兰大的航班在地面上滞留了大约三个小时，而室外温度却高达110多度。</p><p> Tashina 和 Janssen Robinson 与他们 16 岁的侄女和 1 岁的婴儿一起乘坐飞机。住在亚特兰大的罗宾逊一家在家庭团聚后乘飞机回家，他们说飞机上的空调已经打开。但塔西娜说，微弱的气流感觉就像“在阳光下吹风扇”。</p><p>交通运输部正在调查这起事件。达美航空表示正在配合调查，并正在调查导致机上温度不舒服的原因。</p><p>交通部针对这些情况制定<a href="https://www.transportation.gov/individuals/aviation-consumer-protection/tarmac-delays" target="_blank" class="icon none">了消费者保护措施</a>，尽管这些保护措施可能有限。以下是关于停机坪延误期间您的权利的信息。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="444" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822623?width=700&amp;height=444" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> DOT 规则要求航空公司在国内航班延误超过 3 小时、国际航班延误超过 4 小时之前开始转移到乘客可以离开的地方，但有一些例外。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Kena Betancur/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>为什么飞机会卡在停机坪上？</h3><p>联邦航空管理局前高级管理人员、佛罗里达州安柏里德尔航空大学助理教授迈克尔·麦考密克表示，阻碍飞机起飞的天气是地面延误的主要原因之一。</p><p>由于空中交通管制员正在努力减少恶劣天气地区的拥堵，因此距离风暴系统数百英里的乘客可能会遇到地面延误。麦考密克说，严重且频繁的雷暴切断了飞机的航线。当航班无法起飞时，没有足够的登机口供抵达的飞机停放。人员配备或机械问题也可能导致延误。</p><p>纽约机场有限的跑道容量加剧了天气和空中交通管制问题</p>保罗·哈德森 (Paul Hudson)，消费者权益保护组织 FlyersRights 的总裁。<p></p><p>港务局表示，正在对其机场进行投资，包括机场滑行道，以帮助飞机更快地进出跑道。</p><h3>我的航空公司是否因停机坪延误而欠我赔偿？</h3><p>不可以。但他们必须在停机坪延误开始后两小时内为您提供零食和水。即使延误持续很长时间，他们也不需要提供餐点。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>今年夏天您的航空旅行经历如何？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>航空公司必须为可能需要的人提供工作厕所、舒适的机舱温度和医疗护理。没有定义为舒适的设定温度。</p><p>如果您的航班在停机坪延误后延误或取消，您可能需要赔偿。一些航空公司会为因延误或取消而导致的食品、酒店或地面交通提供代金券——只要延误或取消是在他们的控制范围内。 （与天气相关的问题不适用。）</p><h3>航空公司可以让乘客在飞机上停留多长时间？</h3><p>对于国内航班，交通部规则要求航空公司在延误超过三小时之前开始转移到乘客可以离开的地方。这适用于抵达和出发。对于国际航班，时间限制为四个小时。但出于安全、安保和空中交通管制相关原因，它允许例外。</p><p>麦考密克说，例如，如果您的飞机在 30 架飞机的队列中排名第四，那么脱离队列并返回登机口可能会被视为对空中交通运营的干扰。</p><h3>如果我的飞机被困在停机坪上该怎么办？</h3><p>在您有机会下飞机之前，您的选择是有限的。如果您选择在停机坪延误期间下机，航空公司不需要让您重新登机，您可能需要寻找其他航班。</p><p>麦考密克说，无法保证您下飞机后会与行李重聚。</p><p>哈德森说，这些天飞机已经满员，这意味着无法保证您能搭乘下一班航班。</p><p><em>这篇文章可能会更新</em>。</p><p><em>订阅新的</em> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>《华尔街日报》旅游通讯，</em></a><em>了解《华尔街日报》旅游团队的更多提示和见解。</em></p><p>写信给 Allison Pohle，邮箱为<a href="mailto:allison.pohle@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">allison.pohle@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 16:13:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tarmac-delay-rights-airports-9c5b1464</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tarmac-delay-rights-airports-9c5b1464<author><![CDATA[Allison Pohle]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>航空公司</category><category>客运航空公司</category><category>机场</category><category>航空运输</category><category>运输/物流</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>运输</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>联合航空控股</category><category>伦敦大学艺术学院</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>运输</category><category>航空公司</category><category>客运航空公司</category><category>机场</category><category>航空运输</category><category>运输</category><category>后勤</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[What’s Happening in Israel? Protests and Strikes Over Netanyahu’s Judicial Overhaul]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>以色列领导人的举动导致国家分裂，引发大规模抗议，以下是您需要了解的情况<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823207/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="抗议者参加特拉维夫的示威活动。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>抗议者参加特拉维夫的示威活动。伊利亚·叶菲莫维奇/DPA/祖玛出版社<span>伊利亚·叶菲莫维奇/DPA/祖玛出版社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0000724990"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0000724990"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">多夫·利伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 25 日中午 12:08（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>耶路撒冷——近几个月来，数十万以色列人走上全国街头示威，反对总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府计划的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">司法改革</a>。</p><p> 7 月 24 日，执政联盟推动以色列议会获得通过，这是该联盟希望通过的一系列<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">限制法院系统权力的</a>法律中的第一部。在达成妥协的谈判破裂后，该法案在没有任何反对派支持的情况下获得通过。反对派议员走出房间，抵制投票。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡是该国任职时间最长的总理，目前已进入第六个任期，在他的政府于三月份首次尝试通过另一套不同的法案后，内塔尼亚胡使司法立法从失败中恢复过来。在大规模抗议和大罢工导致国家瘫痪后，他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/strike-called-flights-grounded-in-israel-over-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-plan-e8c95930?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">推迟了这项努力</a>，但他在六月份表示，他将以修改后的形式通过这项改革。</p><p>该法律的通过标志着以色列社会的一个关键时刻，可能与该国最高法院摊牌，而该法律旨在遏制该机构的权力。对于数千名表示将退出的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">预备役军人</a>，以及威胁要大规模停工的商界、工会领导人和医疗专业人员来说，这是一个决定性的时刻。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisrael-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列医生周二举行罢工，当局在因总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府进行的司法改革而发生骚乱的夜晚，强行将抗议者从道路上带走。照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>以色列最大的工会以色列总工会表示，他们正在为可能举行的总罢工做准备，一些抗议者正在敦促其采取这样的行动。然而，工会决定不在第一项法案通过后立即宣布大罢工。</p><p>第一项法案通过的第二天，以色列的医生和医务人员举行了罢工。</p><p>此次改革<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-judicial-overhaul-pits-secular-religious-communities-against-each-other-a4177c16?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">引发了该国的分裂</a>，引发了美国等主要盟友的担忧，并在伊朗支持的真主党武装组织沿其北部边境造成的威胁日益加大的情况下，引发了对其军事准备情况的质疑。分析人士警告说，该国可能会陷入宪法危机。</p><p>这是您需要了解的内容。</p><h3>以色列民众为何抗议？</h3><p>在这个拥有 900 万人口的国家，每个周末都有多达 50 万以色列人出来抗议内塔尼亚胡<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/netanyahu-advances-overhaul-of-top-israeli-court-drawing-thousands-of-protesters-ee0287d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">计划的对该国司法机构的改革</a>。</p><p>示威者和该国的政治反对派表示，该计划将削弱以色列本已脆弱的制衡体系，并破坏民主和对少数群体的保护。他们还表示，此次改革将对以色列的民主性格造成致命打击。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-right-wing-lawmakers-aim-to-remake-supreme-court-11668506325?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">关于以色列最高法院的争论</a>部分是由于该国自建国以来法律体系的模糊性造成的。以色列没有成文宪法。相反，法院的判决基于英国普通法、不断发展的以色列先例和一系列基本法，这些法律提供了准宪法的权力。</p><p>围绕最高法院的斗争也成为以色列社会更深层次裂痕的代表。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/story/why-israelis-are-protesting-netanyahu-governments-judicial-overhaul-0933acc5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">抗议活动</a>使自由派、世俗的以色列人（他们将法院视为人权的保障者）与极端正统派以及宗教和政治保守派进行了对立，后者认为法院是实现其政策目标的障碍。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="839" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823210?width=1260&amp;height=839" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">议会通过司法改革提案的第一部分后，耶路撒冷的抗议者。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Orit Ben-Ezzer/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>这场危机的核心是哪些司法变革？</h3><p>内塔尼亚胡的 64 名议员组成的整个联盟于 7 月 24 日投票赞成一项法律，该法律剥夺了最高法院撤销其认为“极其不合理”的政府决定的能力——他们认为这一概念含糊不清，并允许自由派法官推翻政府的意愿。越来越右翼的选民</p><p>这是联盟希望通过的一系列限制法院系统权力的法律中的第一部。接下来是一项法案，该法案将赋予立法者更多选择法官的权力，这一举措比周一通过的法案更具争议性。它可能会在秋季进行投票。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/netanyahu-revives-judicial-overhaul-stripped-of-most-controversial-piece-33160de" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">内塔尼亚胡六月告诉《华尔街日报》</a> ，他将放弃该计划在以色列以外地区最具争议的部分，这将赋予国家立法机构推翻最高法院裁决的权力。</p><p>所谓的“优先条款”将允许议会以 61 名议员的多数票否决最高法院有关立法的决定。这些提案还需要绝大多数法官才能推翻议会法律。批评者表示，拟议的改革实际上将结束对议会的司法审查，因为以色列历史上几乎每个议会联盟都拥有 61 个或更多席位。</p><h3>内塔尼亚胡为何推动司法改革计划？</h3><p>内塔尼亚胡三月份暂停了改革计划，并在大规模抗议后开始<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-calms-after-netanyahu-suspends-judicial-overhaul-b951d2c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">与反对派进行妥协谈判</a>。但在六月下旬，他表示双方未能达成协议，他将继续推进自己修改后的计划。</p><p>这位长期执政的领导人历来都不是改革司法制度的倡导者，但他面临着来自其联盟成员的巨大压力，要求他通过这一改革。联盟成员被广泛认为是该国75年历史上最右翼、民族主义和宗教色彩最浓厚的人。</p><p>关于司法立法的辩论揭示了以色列社会对于犹太国家和民主国家的意义的分歧。该国在成立之初的几十年里是由主要是东欧血统的世俗社会主义者建立和控制的。他们设想了一个文化上犹太教但社会上自由民主的国家。</p><p>近几十年来，代表以色列右翼的不同阶层——宗教犹太复国主义者、定居者、极端正统派和中东裔犹太人——之间的联盟在数量和力量上都在增长。内塔尼亚胡领导的利库德集团本身是世俗的，它已将这些右翼势力联合成一个政治强国。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823214?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡在耶路撒冷举行的议会会议上。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：玛雅·阿莱鲁佐/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>下一步是什么？</h3><p>最高法院现在必须决定是否接受以色列律师协会和反对派成员的请愿书，要求其废除限制其权力的法律。</p><p> 7月24日通过的立法是对以色列所谓基本法之一的修正案——零碎立法，是该国最接近宪法的立法。</p><p>以色列最高法院以前从未废除过基本法。如果法院决定听取请愿书，可能会与政府发生直接冲突。</p><p>以色列国家安全部长伊塔马尔·本-格维尔表示，最高法院否决该法案的举动将被视为“未遂政变”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823222?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列预备役军人在特拉维夫签署一份声明。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Matan Golan/SOPA/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> Will this affect the relationship between Israel and the US?</h3><p> Netanyahu moved ahead with the judicial overhaul despite repeated <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-ambassador-warned-israel-against-going-off-the-rails-with-judicial-overhaul-d612fffa?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">warnings by the Biden administration</a> , including one only hours before the vote, when President Biden issued a public statement, saying the measure was “becoming more divisive, not less.”</p><p> Biden administration officials were quick to insist after the measures passed that the US-Israel relationship remains “ironclad,” as White House Press Secretary Karine Jean-Pierre put it. She didn&#39;t directly answer questions about whether there would be tangible consequences for Israel, describing Biden as a lifelong friend of Israel.</p><p> Biden is unlikely to try to punish Netanyahu by seeking to cut aid to Israel, a move that Congress would likely not support anyway, analysts said. But the Israeli government isn&#39;t likely to entirely avoid paying a price for the vote.</p><p> “It will give fodder to those in Congress, especially on the left who want to pressure the Biden administration to reconsider the relationship,” said Carmiel Arbit, a nonresident fellow at the Atlantic Council, a Washington think tank. “I don&#39;t think it will threaten the relationship, but it will chip away at it over time.”</p><p> <em>This explanatory article may be periodically updated.</em></p><p class="articleTagLine"> —David S. Cloud and Ari Flanzraich contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Dov Lieber at <a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 16:08:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71<author><![CDATA[Dov Lieber]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>National/Public Security</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Risk News</category><category> Military Action</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Itamar Ben-Gvir</category><category> Karine Jean-Pierre</category><category> Carmiel Arbit</category><category>本杰明·内塔尼亚胡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>public security</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>risk news</category><category> military action </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Foreign Minister Replaced After Unexplained Absence]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Qin Gang is removed months after Xi Jinping promoted him to head the Foreign Ministry <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081700"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9F7AF9B6-88BC-4AB6-B4C8-E0CF0C68E116&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchina-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Beijing reappointed top diplomat Wang Yi to replace Qin Gang as foreign minister during an emergency session on Tuesday, without addressing Qin&#39;s mysterious absence. Photo: Florence Lo/Pool Reuters/Associated Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081700"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/chunhan-wong" itemprop="url" rel="author">Chun Han Wong</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 25, 2023 10:15 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> SINGAPORE—Chinese leader Xi Jinping removed his handpicked foreign minister after less than seven months on the job, a surprise move that leaves more questions than answers around <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-shakes-up-government-as-xi-asserts-more-control-over-policy-ffc22275?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">China&#39;s black-box political system.</a></p><p> Qin Gang&#39;s removal comes after his <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-tries-to-reassure-u-s-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">mysterious absence</a> from the public stage over the past month, a disappearance that has sparked speculation about his fate and cast a global spotlight on the Communist Party&#39;s opaque governance of the world&#39;s second-largest economy.</p><p> At a hastily convened session Tuesday, the Chinese legislature&#39;s standing committee decided that Wang Yi, the former foreign minister and currently China&#39;s top diplomat, would retake his old post, which he had relinquished late last year.</p><p> The lawmakers didn&#39;t provide a reason for their decision to remove the 57-year-old Qin, who had succeeded Wang after enjoying an unusually rapid rise through the foreign-service ranks in recent years. Qin&#39;s absence from major diplomatic engagements since late June had <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-tries-to-reassure-u-s-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">fueled rumors inside and outside China</a> about what happened to him.</p><p> China&#39;s Foreign Ministry previously cited health reasons for Qin&#39;s absence from a regional diplomatic meeting in Indonesia earlier this month. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823226?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Wang Yi &#39;s return as foreign minister appears to be an interim appointment, analysts say.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: BERNADETT SZABO/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Wang, a 69-year-old member of the Communist Party&#39;s elite 24-member Politburo, served as foreign minister from early 2013 until December last year. He became China&#39;s top diplomat when he joined the Politburo in October as its leading foreign-affairs specialist.</p><p> In China&#39;s political system, the foreign minister isn&#39;t necessarily the country&#39;s highest-ranking diplomat. That role resides with the most senior foreign-policy official by party rank, who is currently Wang, the director of the office of the party&#39;s Central Foreign Affairs Commission.</p><p> State media reports didn&#39;t mention any change to Wang&#39;s party roles, suggesting he would occupy his Politburo and Foreign Ministry positions concurrently—an arrangement that, after the 1990s, has only taken place during a transition period between officeholders.</p><p> Political analysts say Wang&#39;s return as foreign minister appears to be an interim appointment to buy time while Xi and other senior officials figure out longer-term arrangements. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823223?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Qin Gang working in Cairo earlier this year.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Amr Nabil/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “Qin&#39;s removal shouldn&#39;t be interpreted as a diminishment of Xi Jinping&#39;s power, which extends far wider and deeper than any one single appointment,” said Jude Blanchette, a China analyst at the Washington-based Center for Strategic and International Studies. “And the fact that, for now, Qin keeps some of his party and government positions indicates that there are some unresolved internal issues.”</p><p> State media readouts from Tuesday&#39;s session of the National People&#39;s Congress standing committee didn&#39;t mention any change to Qin&#39;s role as state councilor, a senior government rank in the State Council, China&#39;s cabinet. The State Council&#39;s website continued to list Qin as a state councilor as of Tuesday evening.</p><p> Party authorities haven&#39;t announced any change to Qin&#39;s status as one of 205 full members of the party&#39;s Central Committee, which he joined in October while he was China&#39;s ambassador to the US</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Tuesday&#39;s legislative session was arranged just one day in advance, an unusually short notice, and outside the typical two-month cycle for regular standing committee sessions. This extraordinary session came right after a Politburo meeting on Monday, chaired by Xi.</p><p> “Overall foreign policy won&#39;t likely change in the wake of Qin&#39;s removal, as his role was simply to implement key decisions made by Xi Jinping,” said Blanchette.</p><p> The mystery around Qin has prompted new questions about China&#39;s governance under Xi, whose Communist Party has doubled down on its penchant for secrecy and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-locks-information-on-the-country-inside-a-black-box-9c039928" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">frustrated outsiders&#39; efforts</a> to access information about developments in a leading economic powerhouse.</p><p> Considered a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-promotes-u-s-ambassador-to-foreign-minister-11672409545?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">trusted aide to Xi</a> , Qin had enjoyed an unusually rapid rise within China&#39;s foreign service in recent years after serving as protocol chief for the Chinese leader. Qin was appointed Beijing&#39;s ambassador to Washington in 2021 despite having no formal background directly handling US relations, before joining the Central Committee and winning promotion to foreign minister late last year—bucking precedent in a system that traditionally has valued experience in addition to political connections.</p><p> Political analysts say Qin&#39;s close association with Xi has made his absence particularly intriguing. A dearth of information about Qin&#39;s whereabouts has fueled speculation on social media, including around the possibility of an extramarital affair.</p><p> The Chinese Foreign Ministry first addressed Qin&#39;s disappearance on July 11, when it said at a regular news briefing that he wouldn&#39;t attend an international gathering of foreign ministers in Jakarta because of health reasons, without giving any details. Since then, the ministry&#39;s spokespeople have generally sidestepped questions about Qin.</p><p> In China&#39;s opaque political system, health issues are often cited as the reason for a senior official&#39;s absence. While the explanation is often genuine, party insiders say, it can sometimes serve as cover for political problems.</p><p> When Wang Lijun, the former police chief in the inland megacity of Chongqing, went missing in February 2012, municipal authorities said he was taking “vacation-style treatment” for stress and overwork, though in reality he had fled to the US consulate in the nearby city of Chengdu to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390444100404577643450001423304" target="_blank" class="icon none">seek asylum</a> .</p><p> Beijing&#39;s move to replace Qin as foreign minister won&#39;t quell speculation around his fate, since it leaves many questions about what caused his prolonged absence, said Alfred Wu, an associate professor at the Lee Kuan Yew School of Public Policy in Singapore.</p><p> At Tuesday&#39;s legislative session, lawmakers also named Pan Gongsheng as governor of the People&#39;s Bank of China. The move had been expected after the 60-year-old Pan, who had been deputy governor since 2012, was <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-plans-to-appoint-a-new-central-bank-governor-56a878ea" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">appointed as the central bank&#39;s top party official</a> earlier this month.</p><p> The veteran economist and banker had been <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-man-charged-with-steering-the-yuan-through-chinas-economic-turmoil-37574af8" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">getting ready to retire</a> in the weeks before Xi picked him to lead the central bank at a time when the Chinese yuan has been on a downward slide, The Wall Street Journal has reported.</p><p> Write to Chun Han Wong at <a href="mailto:chunhan.wong@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">chunhan.wong@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 14:15:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad<author><![CDATA[Chun Han Wong]]></author><category> Economic News</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>International Relations</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> economic news</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The ‘Lazy-Girl Job’ Is In Right Now. Here’s Why.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Rather than lean in, young workers say they want jobs that can be done from home, come with a cool boss and end at 5 pm sharp <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819062/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo Illustration by Bea Oyster/The Wall Street Journal, iStock (2), Getty Images <span>Photo Illustration by Bea Oyster/The Wall Street Journal, iStock (2), Getty Images</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001062328"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001062328"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/katie-mogg" itemprop="url" rel="author">Katie Mogg</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 25, 2023 9:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-career-goal-of-the-moment-is-a-lazy-girl-job-f5075c4e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Some people would call Victoria Bilodeau&#39;s decision to work as a freelance digital marketer a move to gain work-life balance. She calls it a “lazy-girl job.”</p><p> Bilodeau, 23 years old, says she used to work 10-hour days as an environmental technician, helping clean up low-level radioactive dirt for $26 an hour. Now, she logs about three hours a day promoting makeup and skin-care products online. She earns less than she used to, but in her newly abundant free time, she exercises, meditates and plays with her cats, Jinx and Fang. Living with her boyfriend in Belleville, Ontario, helps defray expenses.</p><p> “I really do have such a chill life in comparison to what it was,” she says.</p><p> Bilodeau and scores of other women online are bragging about their work setup using the hashtag #lazygirljob. To fans, the ideal lazy-girl job is one that can be done from home, comes with a chill boss, ends at 5 pm sharp and earns between $60,000 and $80,000 a year—enough to afford the basic comforts of young-adult life, yet not enough to feel compelled to work overtime. Veterans of such jobs say roles such as “digital marketing associate,” “customer-success manager” and “office administrator” are good bets for achieving the lazy-girl lifestyle.</p><p> The phenomenon, essentially the opposite of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sheryl-sandbergs-legacy-of-leaning-in-11654128723?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">“leaning in,”</a> has detractors, who say that aspiring to a lazy-girl job is the wrong attitude for building a meaningful career. Yet, many young women who have branded themselves “lazy girls” online insist they are anything but. After growing up hearing about the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/burned-out-maybe-you-should-care-less-about-your-job-11633320061?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">horrors of overwork</a> , they say they&#39;re happy in their jobs and celebrate striking work-life balance gold.</p><p> The term has generated close to 18 million views on TikTok, where videos often show women typing on their keyboards, with overlaid text about the perks they enjoy, like a manager who doesn&#39;t micromanage and a no-pressure schedule that permits midday dog walks.</p><p> Like <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/if-your-gen-z-co-workers-are-quiet-quitting-heres-what-that-means-11660260608?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">quiet quitting</a> before it, the lazy-girl job is the latest iteration of 20- and 30-somethings of both genders redrawing the blurry line between life and work postpandemic. (The term follows in a long line of girl-themed trends, like <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/BL-ATWORKB-1791?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">“girlboss”</a> and “girl dinner”—basically a plate of snacks—intended to be both self-deprecating and aspirational.)</p><h3> Not just for girls</h3><p> Six in 10 workers say they&#39;re putting in less than maximum effort, according to Gallup&#39;s Global Workplace report this year. In the <a href="https://www.gallup.com/workplace/349484/state-of-the-global-workplace-2022-report.aspx" target="_blank" class="icon none">Gallup survey</a> of more than 120,000 working adults, the biggest complaint from those workers was their workplace&#39;s culture.</p><p> Plenty of men have posted to more anonymous platforms, such as the “antiwork” community on Reddit, to lament the downsides of their jobs, too. They gripe about critical bosses, low pay and feeling afraid to take time off.</p><p> Michael Durwin, a senior social-media strategist, says he isn&#39;t antiwork, but does believe American <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-backlash-against-quiet-quitting-is-getting-loud-11661391232?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hustle culture</a> is toxic at times. He doesn&#39;t understand why a woman would brand herself a “lazy girl,” though he gets the ethos behind the movement.</p><p> “I think younger women are using it almost in a way that they don&#39;t understand the damage it can do,” the 54-year-old said.</p><p> Durwin&#39;s own quest for work-life balance during the pandemic led him to the kind of remote social-media job that many <strong>&nbsp;</strong> avowed lazy girls might aspire to. It&#39;s flexible enough that he can put his daughter&#39;s hair into pigtails before taking the kids to school and pick them up afterward to shuttle them to doctors&#39; appointments or playdates with friends.</p><p> “My children don&#39;t remember a time when Daddy wasn&#39;t home when they got home,” he says.</p><h3> The original lazy girl</h3><p> Gabrielle Judge, a 26-year-old career influencer, says she coined the term “lazy-girl job” in May.</p><p> Judge, whose TikTok, Instagram and LinkedIn accounts focus on work-life balance, says she knew “lazy” would have a negative connotation, but could start a conversation. Lazy-girl jobs aren&#39;t roles where you can slack off, she says, but career paths where “your work-life balance should feel so awesome that you almost feel like you&#39;re being lazy.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="article__tiktok"><amp-tiktok width="325" height="575" data-src="https://www.tiktok.com/@gabrielle_judge/video/7236129804066524459"></amp-tiktok></div></div><p> Before becoming a TikTok career influencer, Judge says she worked her own lazy-girl job in Denver, as an account manager for a tech company. The work-from-home role paid well and came with benefits such as financial credits for fitness classes and spa services, she says. Not only was there no overtime, there was no traditional 9 to 5, so she could log off once her tasks for the day were done.</p><p> She quit after a year, when layoffs at her company had remaining employees taking on <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-promotion-that-comes-without-the-pay-raise-1534944636?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">more work for no pay</a> raise. Suddenly, the gig wasn&#39;t a lazy-girl job anymore. Around the same time, her social-media content began to gain traction.</p><p> Ember Rose Gilliam, 21, says she hates the term lazy-girl job, “but the energy behind it, I very much agree with.”</p><p> She works at a real-estate company where she&#39;s been promoted twice, most recently to an associate project manager making $63,000 a year. She describes her role liaising between project managers and accountants to ensure financial and regulatory compliance as a dream job. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/8a558146-1dbb-453c-8995-40b83b90f57e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Charging through her “head-down” tasks takes two to three hours a day, Gilliam says. The rest of her 40-hour week is spent on call, leaving her with free time and flexibility to work from Miami, Chicago and Las Vegas, and take courses on LinkedIn Learning. She recently finished classes on working smarter, not harder, and boosting productivity using AI tools.</p><p> Gilliam&#39;s boss, Ciara Glasgow, says the job will ramp up to a busier 40-hour week with more training. Nonetheless, Glasgow wants her team to feel professionally challenged without burning out and doesn&#39;t worry about how people order their days so long as work gets done.</p><p> Gilliam appreciates the autonomy: “I have never answered a ping or a call outside of my office hours.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> 分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What career decisions have you made to help you achieve a healthy work-life balance?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Write to Katie Mogg at <a href="mailto:katie.mogg@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">katie.mogg@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-career-goal-of-the-moment-is-a-lazy-girl-job-f5075c4e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-career-goal-of-the-moment-is-a-lazy-girl-job-f5075c4e<author><![CDATA[Katie Mogg]]></author><category> wsjlifework</category><category>广告/营销/公共关系</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>营销服务</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>职业规划/管理</category><category>General Labor Issues</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>职业生涯规划</category><category>管理</category><category>general labor issues</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>广告</category><category>营销</category><category>公共关系</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>营销服务</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Israel Faces New Security Threats if Protesting Military Reservists Refuse to Serve]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Country faces growing risk from Iran-backed Hezbollah while ties with Washington are strained <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081692"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisraels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Israel&#39;s doctors went on strike on Tuesday and authorities forcibly removed protesters from roadways during a night of unrest over a judicial overhaul carried out by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu&#39;s government. Photo: Amir Levy/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081692"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/david-s-cloud" itemprop="url" rel="author">David S. Cloud</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dov Lieber</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 25, 2023 8:33 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Months of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">internal turmoil</a> surrounding a judicial overhaul pushed through Parliament by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu have left Israel facing a challenging security environment, with questions about its military readiness, a growing threat from the Iranian-backed Hezbollah militant group along its northern border and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-netanyahu-agree-to-meet-later-this-year-247c33f7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">strained ties</a> with Washington, its biggest ally.</p><p> Hassan Nasrallah, leader of the Lebanese political and militant group Hezbollah, said that Monday was “the worst day in the history of the [Zionist] entity, as some of its people say,” and that the country is a “regional power whose faith, awareness and self-confidence have started to deteriorate into the crisis it&#39;s experiencing today.”</p><p> The legislation passed Monday that <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">restricts the power of the country&#39;s Supreme Court</a> has moved beyond being a domestic political issue after thousands of military reservists threatened to refuse to report for duty in protest, a potentially damaging blow to a military that is highly dependent on volunteers with years of experience serving as fighter pilots, intelligence analysts and special operations troops in continuing operations.</p><p> Though it remains to be seen how many will follow through on that promise, an Israeli military official said Monday that limited numbers of reservists have already stopped showing up for training. The impact of their decision may not be felt for months, but senior military officials warned Netanyahu that <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the legislation was harming</a> unity in the military&#39;s ranks and could affect its long-term readiness for battle. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823125?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> People in Jerusalem marched in protest of a judiciary overhaul on Monday.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Amir Levy/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Some reservists might notify their commanders in the coming days and weeks that they won&#39;t be reporting for duty. Israeli reservists serve regularly throughout the year, ranging from a day a week to a full month a year.</p><p> Netanyahu, in a speech Monday night, called on protesters to leave the country&#39;s military out of “any political controversy.”</p><p> “We all know that the IDF relies on dedicated reservists who love this country,” he said, referring to the Israel Defense Forces. “Calls for refusal to serve harm the security of every citizen of the state.”</p><p> The reservists say they aren&#39;t opposing a political position but what they view as legislation that will undermine democracy.</p><p> The IDF has 169,000 active duty troops and 465,000 reservists and remains the Middle East&#39;s most formidable force, supplied with some of the most advanced drones and other weapons from Israel&#39;s technology sector and from the US, which provides Israel with $3.8 billion in annual military assistance.</p><p> If reservists in military jobs requiring highly developed skills stop volunteering for duty and training, the IDF would still have the capability to handle most threats. In a security crisis, many of the reservists who have pledged to quit would be likely to return to duty, analysts said. The real impact is likely to be more long-term, analysts said.</p><p> “The IDF relies on the fact that Israel is a small country where everyone who is not an ultra-Orthodox Jew agrees to serve,” said Michael Koplow, chief policy officer at the Israel Policy Forum, an American-Jewish group. “Once that gets broken, I think it&#39;s going to be very hard to fix it.”</p><p> The measure approved Monday by the Israeli parliament, known as the Knesset, seeks to restrict use of a legal standard known as reasonableness by the Israeli Supreme Court, which has in the past struck down government or executive decisions by asserting that they were decisions that are “extremely unreasonable.” Supporters say the doctrine allows the courts to overrule the will of elected officials for political purposes.</p><p> On Saturday, dozens of former top security officials, including former heads of the military, the Mossad foreign spy agency and the Shin Bet domestic security agency wrote a letter to Netanyahu, supporting the reservist protest and warning the prime minister that his policies were eroding the social cohesion required to maintain a “people&#39;s army” model such as the one in Israel. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823127?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu attends a vote on a bill to restrict the power of the Supreme Court.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: AMIR COHEN/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The judicial overhaul has drawn intense opposition from some quarters of Israeli society, who claim the changes are aimed at preventing the Supreme Court from blocking Netanyahu&#39;s far-right coalition partners from pursuing controversial legislation that could include annexing parts of the occupied West Bank, asserting a stronger Jewish presence at Jerusalem&#39;s contested holy sites or significantly expanding Israeli settlements across the West Bank.</p><p> Many of these goals are at odds with longstanding US policy in the Middle East, which supports the creation of an independent Palestinian state alongside Israel.</p><p> Netanyahu moved ahead with the judicial overhaul despite repeated warnings by the Biden administration, including one on Sunday only hours before the vote, when President Biden issued a public statement, saying the measure was “becoming more divisive, not less.”</p><p> Biden administration officials were quick to insist after the measures passed that the US-Israel relationship remains “ironclad,” as White House press secretary Karine Jean-Pierre</p> put it. She didn&#39;t directly answer questions about whether there would be tangible consequences for Israel, describing Biden as a lifelong friend of Israel. <p></p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823133?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Hezbollah fighters take part in a military exercise, in Aaramta, Lebanon.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: anwar amro/AFP/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Biden is unlikely to try to punish Netanyahu by seeking to cut aid to Israel, a move that Congress would likely not support anyway, analysts said. But the Israeli government isn&#39;t likely to entirely avoid paying a price entirely for the vote.</p><p> “It will give fodder to those in Congress, especially on the left who want to pressure the Biden administration to reconsider the relationship,” said Carmiel Arbit, a nonresident fellow at the Atlantic Council, a Washington think tank. “I don&#39;t think it will threaten the relationship, but it will chip away at it over time.”</p><p> The judicial overhaul is being closely watched by Washington and other allies fearful of the direction Israel is taking, but also by Middle East adversaries eager to exploit any sign of weakness. The contest over the judicial overhaul is occurring as Israel&#39;s geopolitical position in the Middle East has eroded this year. Netanyahu had harbored hopes of normalizing ties with Saudi Arabia, but Riyadh instead re-established diplomatic <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-arabia-iran-restore-relations-in-deal-brokered-by-china-406393a1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">relations with Iran</a> , which has stepped up its support for Hezbollah and other <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-is-recruiting-militant-allies-to-launch-attacks-against-israel-c40f369f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">anti-Israel proxies</a> .</p><p> Hezbollah in particular has become increasingly aggressive along Israel&#39;s northern border, according to Israeli security officials. They say Hezbollah is quietly building up forces in key locations along the border, with plain white trailers with antennas popping out of them. The sites are so close to the border that men from the Lebanese side often throw rocks at Israeli soldiers. They have also cut the security fence on the border, sending soldiers scrambling. Israeli officials say the sites are manned by men in both civilian clothes and combat fatigues.</p><p> Israeli officials say Hezbollah operatives have never operated so openly. “They are not disguised anymore,” an Israeli military official said. “It&#39;s a new phenomenon.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823129?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Palestinian gunmen from the Al Aqsa Martyrs Brigades are seen in the Balata refugee camp in the West Bank.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Nasser Ishtayeh/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Along with other recent actions by Hezbollah, Israeli officials say this is the most openly aggressive the Iran-backed group has been since the two sides fought a 34-day war in 2006 in which 165 Israelis died and 1,100 Lebanese were killed.</p><p> The months of turmoil sparked by the judicial overhaul have also coincided with a deadly conflict with Palestinian militants in the West Bank. The Israeli military has conducted frequent raids in Palestinian cities and refugee camps, with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-raids-west-bank-with-armored-vehicles-and-drones-killing-at-least-eight-17e0c7c8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">bloody confrontations</a> ensuing with well-armed militants. Last month, Israeli military helicopters fired in the direction of Palestinian militants during a gunbattle in the West Bank, the first such escalation in years.</p><p> Hezbollah has grown bolder in part due to the perception by Iran and Hezbollah that Israel is internally weak because of prolonged political unrest, analysts and Israeli security officials say. Iran might still hesitate to try to strike Israel directly with suicide drones or other weapons, but it could unleash its proxy forces.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What do you think will be the ripple effects of Prime Minister Netanyahu&#39;s attempt to overhaul the judiciary?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Hezbollah has an arsenal of over 100,000 rockets, which are aimed at Israel, much of them hidden in homes and other civilian sites around southern Lebanon, Israeli military officials say. Hezbollah has also produced hundreds of precision-guided missiles that can hit anywhere in Israel, such as sensitive fuel installations or military sites, Israeli officials say.</p><p> Hezbollah has published a number of videos in recent years meant to show Israel how much damage its guided missile arsenal can do.</p><p> “We&#39;ve seen as these protests have gone along that Hezbollah has been testing Israel,” said David Schenker, a former State Department official who was responsible for the Middle East and now a fellow at the Washington Institute for Near East Policy, a Washington policy organization. “Because Israel has been going after Iran for so long in Syria, I think there is still enough deterrence for Tehran, but the proxies are not bound by the same rules of the game.”</p><p> Write to David S. Cloud at <a href="mailto:david.cloud@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">david.cloud@wsj.com</a> and Dov Lieber at <a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 12:33:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff<author><![CDATA[David S. CloudDov Lieber]]></author><category> wsjworld</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Civil Unrest</category><category> National/Public Security</category><category> Society/Community</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>武装部队</category><category>International Relations</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Risk News</category><category>社会问题</category><category>Espionage</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>本杰明·内塔尼亚胡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>civil unrest</category><category>国家的</category><category>public security</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>armed forces</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>risk news</category><category> social issues</category><category> espionage</category><category> terrorism</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Soap Maker Cracks the Code to ‘Made in America’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Bath &amp; Body Works persuaded suppliers to set up production in an Ohio city near its headquarters <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822326/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Label  manufacturer CCL is one of the suppliers for Bath &amp; Body Works in New Albany, Ohio." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Label manufacturer CCL is one of the suppliers for Bath &amp; Body Works in New Albany, Ohio. <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001075938"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001075938"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/austen-hufford" itemprop="url" rel="author">Austen Hufford</a></span> / Photographs by Maddie McGarvey for The Wall Street Journal</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 25, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bath-body-works-us-manufacturing-413cf9d0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> NEW ALBANY, Ohio—A $7.95 bottle of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BBWI" class="company-name">Bath &amp; Body Works</a> foaming hand soap used to take three months to put together. The pieces had to travel more than 13,000 miles from China, Canada and Virginia to the company&#39;s Ohio distribution center.</p><p> Bath &amp; Body Works decided it needed to get new products to market more quickly. The result was a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-companies-on-pace-to-bring-home-record-number-of-overseas-jobs-11660968061?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">production</a> initiative with little parallel in corporate America.</p><p> Now every step of production occurs at plants just feet from each other on the company&#39;s dedicated “beauty park” on the outskirts of Columbus. One factory makes the foaming pump and mechanism. Another makes the bottle itself, a third makes the label, a fourth makes the soap, fills the bottle, attaches the label and screws on the top.第五个包装它。将一瓶酒送到配送中心的时间缩短为 21 天和几英里。 Bath &amp; Body Works 在自营商店销售的大部分产品都是现场制作的。</p><p> The effort, which started in 2008, required a lot of negotiation with sometimes skeptical suppliers.该园区包括 10 家制造商和数百万平方英尺的生产和仓库空间，生产高峰期间有 5,000 名员工在那里工作。 Bath &amp; Body Works had sales of $7.56 billion last year, increasing annual revenue by more than $2 billion since 2019.</p><p> “I look at BBW as a composer and a conductor of a symphony,” said Bath &amp; Body Works supply-chain executive Susanna Zhu.</p><p> Bringing production closer to home has become a priority for many companies. Disruptions from Covid-19, severe weather, trade wars, geopolitical tensions and stuck ships left consumers without the couches and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-is-the-supply-chain-still-so-snarled-we-explain-with-a-hot-tub-11629987531?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hot tubs</a> they wanted. The Biden administration is spending hundreds of billions of dollars aimed at boosting the domestic presence of industries deemed strategic, including electric cars, batteries and semiconductors.</p><p> The government money, along with roaring consumer demand and persistent supply-chain issues, are leading to a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-manufacturing-factory-jobs-comeback-3ce0c52c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">factory building boom</a> , with spending at its highest level in at least 20 years. Over the next decade, public and private investment will amount to $3.5 trillion, the government estimates.</p><p> Bath &amp; Body Works&#39; initiative proved particularly helpful during the pandemic. While competitors struggled with shortages, BBW&#39;s suppliers on location shared raw materials and even employees to make more hand sanitizer and other in-demand goods. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822324?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Daniel Rice, a press operator at CCL, works the line.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Chief Executive Gina Boswell</p> said locating corporate executives just a short drive away from key manufacturers allows problems to be fixed and new products developed quickly.<p></p><p> “That&#39;s magical, especially when you need speed and agility,” she said.</p><p> The company, which like many retailers benefited from increased consumer spending in the pandemic, said <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bath-body-works-financial-chief-wendy-arlin-to-leave-e6b40c91?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">sales could fall</a> this year.</p><p> One <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/craftsman-america-wrench-stanley-black-decker-reshoring-factory-1125792f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">challenge</a> to replicating BBW&#39;s model is that factories don&#39;t operate in bubbles, but rely on networks of suppliers, parts and expertise—and moving those networks is costly.一旦建立了这样的网络，它往往就会陷入困境。</p><p> Land, labor and compliance with environmental and zoning laws also generally cost more in the US than in China and developing countries.</p><p> What works for soap and the two dozen other products BBW makes won&#39;t necessarily translate to smartphones, blenders or even backpacks with highly specialized supply chains deeply rooted in Asia. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822322?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Hari Poudel packages Bath &amp; Body Works soap at KDC/One, another supplier in New Albany.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Semiconductor manufacturers and raw steel producers require massive upfront investment and economies of scale. BBW 模型更适合利用范围经济，即制造商生产多种产品。 Bath &amp; Body Works can roll out around 7,000 new scented products a year.</p><p> BBW, whose headquarters is about 10 miles from the beauty park, was founded by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/leslie-wexner-to-leave-board-of-l-brands-11616072589?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Les Wexner</a> as part of his retail conglomerate, L Brands.身体产品销售店从 1990 年的 27 家店增加到 1999 年的 1,000 多家，截至 4 月份已达到 1,810 家。 In 2021 L Brands spun off its</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/VSCO" class="company-name">Victoria&#39;s Secret</a> lingerie stores and changed its name to Bath &amp; Body Works, focusing exclusively on that brand.<p></p><p> For its beauty campus, the company chose New Albany, a planned community close to a major highway and a day&#39;s drive from nearly half the country&#39;s population.</p><p> New Albany wanted to diversify its white-collar economy.为了吸引 BBW，该市创建了分区并安装了基础设施，自身花费 600 万美元，州政府花费 300 万美元。 The early factories opened on the 450-acre site in 2011. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/818b84a5-1525-40bd-9eac-752c4fe195f1.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> To make it happen, BBW had to persuade its best suppliers to move.对于供应商来说，好处是继续与快速增长的护肤品销售商开展业务，并获得 BBW 在一定年限内的销量保证。缺点：花费数百万美元搬迁生产并购买新设备。</p><p> Rieke Packaging, which makes dispensing pumps for soap bottles, didn&#39;t know if it was going to be worth the investment.当时，Rieke 在中国的工厂生产该泵。 Rieke 在印第安纳州几个小时路程外有一家现有工厂，有可能为该公园供货，但 Bath &amp; Body Works 表示希望在现场建工厂。</p><p> “From a supplier perspective, there was a lot of resistance,” said Craig Miller, who worked for Rieke at the time and now works in supply chain and manufacturing for a pharmaceutical company. “你希望我们购买更多设备。我们的租赁率将是印第安纳州农村地区的两倍。得了吧，这听起来一点也不好玩。”</p><p> Rieke decided to make the several-million dollar investment in New Albany. “这是一个不容错过的机会，”米勒说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822319?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Corwin Strong works on quality control at Rieke in New Albany.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Moving production to Ohio wasn&#39;t easy. Factories had to contend with planning officials, high labor and construction costs and even endangered bats.</p><p> Jeff Stouffer worked for Bath &amp; Body Works in new product launches and later joined a supplier that made perfumes and filled bottles, which opened up a new factory at the campus around 2015. He and other executives met with city and business park officials more than a dozen times to discuss the aesthetics of the relatively small factory, negotiating over everything from the color of the walls to the size of the company&#39;s sign.他说，这就像一个服用类固醇的房主协会。</p><p> “They are very rigid about what it looks like,” he said.</p><p> The possible presence of a species of endangered bats prevented the removal of trees on the site, delaying construction for several months.</p><p> Still, almost every company has expanded beyond their initial investment.</p><p> “It&#39;s going to be a 2- to 3-year heavy lift for a payout in 5 to 10 years from now,” Stouffer said.</p><p> Keeping costs down was the biggest challenge.</p><p> Not every production step took place in Ohio at first. Rieke 最初在新奥尔巴尼模制了两个外部塑料部件，可以由多种颜色制成。 It would then attach them to the inner core of the pump, which was still made in China.</p><p> Around 2020, Bath &amp; Body Works said it really wanted the entire foaming soap pump to be produced in the US BBW also didn&#39;t want to pay more than the approximately 20 to 25 cents per unit it was paying, according to Will Nguyen, an engineer who then worked for Rieke and now works as a consulting engineer.</p><p> The two sides negotiated a multiyear supplier agreement to bring pump engine production to the campus from China.阮说，几个月来，我们并不清楚这种情况是否会发生。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822332?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Bottles of Bath &amp; Body Works soap at KDC/One.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Rieke agreed to make the entire pump in Ohio at essentially the same unit cost, and Bath &amp; Body Works helped Rieke get access to volume guarantees and global purchasing and supplier deals with other companies, said Nguyen.</p><p> Now Rieke had to figure out how to make the pumps in Ohio—profitably.他们转向自动化。</p><p> In China, building the 13-part pump was a manual process using lots of workers who handled tiny springs and balls. Rieke 的母公司 TriMas Packaging 的高管马克·博克斯 (Mark Box) 表示：“我们无法复制在俄亥俄州中部海外进行的手动流程，但让机器来复制这项工作却很复杂。” “你的零件非常小，移动速度非常快。最轻微的事情都可能导致堵塞。”</p><p> The machines had to make a pump tight enough to keep the liquid inside but not so tight that it won&#39;t operate.这些机器还必须处理塑料和其他原材料在运输过程中的差异。</p><p> Nguyen estimates that production in the US employs around 10 people and required $12 million in capital investment, versus employing around 50 people with under $2 million in investment for similar production capacity in China.</p><p> The automation and proximity means that pumps and their parts can arrive and be fully created in under a month, compared with five months previously. Rieke sells around 300 million pumps to Bath &amp; Body Works a year.</p><p> New Albany thinks the beauty campus can be a model for other companies and communities. It has attracted an <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMGN" class="company-name">Amgen</a> pharmaceutical plant. Last year Intel chose New Albany as the site of a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/intel-to-invest-at-least-20-billion-in-ohio-chip-making-facility-11642750760?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">$20 billion semiconductor facility</a> . The company said the Intel plant would attract dozens of new local suppliers, including semiconductor equipment makers and other materials providers. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822327?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> People work on molds for Bath &amp; Body Works bottles at Axium in New Albany.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The success of the park, and its thousands of employees during the peak season, means that some of the closely located manufacturers are worried about labor shortages. Bath &amp; Body Works has recently allowed some suppliers to open up factories in other parts of Ohio to attract new workers.</p><p> BBW&#39;s strategy today revolves around the unique properties of its beauty park: new products, delivered quickly. Bath &amp; Body Works regularly rolls out fresh aromas and places a premium on fast design and production.这种模式使 BBW 能够收取高价，避免折扣和剩菜，并有助于弥补本地制造的额外成本。</p><p> The Wild Sand aroma (fragrance notes: prickly pear fruit, cactus flower and warm agave nectar), launched earlier this month, is available as a hand soap, candle, shower gel, perfume, sanitizer spray, body lotion and self tanner.</p><p> Unlike most retailers, which preorder all of their products for the season months in advance, Bath &amp; Body Works aims to preorder around two-thirds.然后，它会密切监控销售情况，并为获胜产品下额外的“即时”订单。</p><p> “Within literally a week, that&#39;s what&#39;s getting shipped,” said Nicholas Whitley, chief executive at soap maker and filler KDC/One.</p><p> Being co-located means manufacturers can use a campus shipping service to easily send samples to the next stage in the process or to a Bath &amp; Body Works executive for signoff, no overnight shipping required.商店里的东西的气味、感觉或外观很难通过 Zoom 通话传达。</p><p> “There are glitters, holographics that don&#39;t translate as well,” said Tom DeCicco, a graphics manager at label maker CCL Label. “You can&#39;t get that in the picture.”</p><p> Write to Austen Hufford at <a href="mailto:austen.hufford@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">austen.hufford@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bath-body-works-us-manufacturing-413cf9d0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bath-body-works-us-manufacturing-413cf9d0<author><![CDATA[Austen Hufford]]></author><category> leder</category><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>摄影委托</category><category>wsjwashington</category><category>零售批发</category><category>Cosmetics/Perfume Retailing</category><category>服装零售</category><category>专业零售</category><category>零售</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Supply Chain</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Bath &amp; Body Works</category><category> BBWI</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>supply chain</category><category>零售</category><category>批发的</category><category>化妆品</category><category>perfume retailing</category><category>服装零售</category><category>专业零售</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ukraine’s Stalled Offensive Puts Biden in Uneasy Political Position]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>由于实际进展缓慢，政府对基辅与莫斯科谈判的希望逐渐破灭<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822600/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="乌克兰士兵向乌克兰东部扎波罗热地区的俄罗斯阵地开火。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>乌克兰士兵向乌克兰东部扎波罗热地区的俄罗斯阵地开火。 Dmytro Smoliyenko/Ukrinform/Zuma Press <span>Dmytro Smoliyenko/Ukrinform/Zuma Press</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001079729"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001079729"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gordon-lubold" itemprop="url" rel="author">戈登·卢伯德 (Gordon Lubold)</a></span> 、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michael-r-gordon" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈克尔·R·戈登 (Michael R. Gordon)</a></span> 、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/warren-p-strobel" itemprop="url" rel="author">沃伦·P·史特罗贝尔 (Warren P. Strobel)</a></span>和</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 25 日中午 12:00（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-stalled-offensive-puts-biden-in-uneasy-political-position-6f686ab5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>西方官员表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-seeks-to-divert-ukrainian-forces-away-from-counteroffensive-80580e89?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，乌克兰对根深蒂固的俄罗斯侵略者的反攻步伐</a>缓慢，使得今年结束战斗的谈判的希望变得渺茫，并引发了无休止冲突的担忧。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-lack-of-weaponry-and-training-risks-stalemate-in-fight-with-russia-f51ecf9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">潜在的僵局</a>将考验拜登总统向乌克兰提供数十亿美元军事援助的既定战略，以使基辅能够以强势地位与俄罗斯进行谈判。它还可能挑战西方持续供应本已短缺的武器的能力，并为那些反对美国支持战争的人提供政治素材。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “显然，当事情进展顺利时，提供更多支持会更容易，”前美国驻乌克兰大使、扩大对基辅军事援助的倡导者约翰·赫布斯特说。但他说，拜登政府除了继续提供武器外别无选择。</p><p>赫布斯特补充说，从乌克兰撤军，甚至允许俄罗斯取得部分胜利，“将是拜登外交政策的标志性失败，这将使阿富汗撤军相形见绌”。赫布斯特目前供职于华盛顿大西洋理事会智囊团。</p><p>然而，美国的“坚持到底”战略也存在一些风险。拜登把他的外交政策信誉押在了一场他称之为民主与威权主义之间的斗争的冲突上。他已向基辅提供了超过 430 亿美元的安全援助，但<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mccarthy-opposes-extra-ukraine-spending-after-debt-deal-cf967c6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在国会面临来自一些共和党成员的挑战</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=8ADA4C1F-0418-43CF-B08A-6EBE0A657F3A&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fukraines-stalled-offensive-puts-biden-in-uneasy-political-position-6f686ab5&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The recent turmoil in Russia could provide an opportunity for Ukraine&#39;s battlefield forces. WSJ reporter Ian Lovett and retired Brigadier Gen. Mark Kimmitt break down what might be next for the Ukrainian counteroffensive. Photo Illustration: Jeremy Shuback/WSJ<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>On Thursday, 13 Senate Republicans backed an amendment to the annual military spending bill that would have limited the availability of funds for Ukraine.该修正案失败了，国会其他共和党人对乌克兰的支持依然强劲。</p><p> As Biden moves toward a presidential contest next year, Russian President Vladimir Putin has more of an incentive to try to outlast the West. Two of the top contenders for the Republican nomination—former President Donald Trump and Florida Gov. Ron DeSantis—have suggested they might temper military support for Ukraine.</p><p>俄罗斯也没有表现出任何谈判的意愿。随着对乌克兰的入侵陷入困境， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-arrests-militant-right-wing-critic-igor-girkin-in-widening-crackdown-3b6308?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">普京面临着国内的批评者</a>，他们说他没有足够积极地进行战争。</p><p> “俄罗斯人非常乐意谈论乌克兰的投降，”外交关系委员会杰出研究员托马斯·格雷厄姆说。 “我认为他们对目前尚未解决乌克兰危机的任何谈判都不太感兴趣。”</p><p>乌克兰于6月初发起反攻，旨在夺回被莫斯科占领的近20%的乌克兰领土中的部分领土。虽然乌克兰夺回了部分领土，但尚未取得可能迫使俄罗斯坐到谈判桌前的突破。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822598?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">拜登总统已向乌克兰提供超过 430 亿美元的安全援助。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：亨里克·蒙哥马利/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>拜登在本月早些时候<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-visit-cements-finlands-pivot-away-from-neutrality-3fd65237?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">访问赫尔辛基</a>时表示：“我的希望和预期是，你们会看到乌克兰在攻势上取得重大进展，并在某个地方通过谈判达成解决方案。”</p><p>由于俄罗斯和乌克兰都不愿意谈判，白宫目前别无选择，只能坚持到底，希望最终能在战场上取得突破，对抗根深蒂固的俄罗斯军队，或者莫斯科出现新的政治裂痕。</p><p>美国官员承认反攻进展缓慢，但表示，在乌克兰派遣更多战斗旅之前评估反攻效果还为时过早，尤其是那些在美国欧洲基地接受过装甲机动战训练的旅。</p><p>一位美国官员表示：“如果他们承诺储备，但储备不成功，那么我们将不得不确定未来的方向。”</p><p>美国国务卿安东尼·布林肯周日在接受 CNN 采访时表示，攻势仍处于初期阶段，自 2022 年 2 月俄罗斯发动全面入侵以来，乌克兰“已收回了最初缴获的约 50%”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822597?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰敖德萨，工人在罢工后清理瓦砾。俄罗斯几乎没有表现出谈判的意愿。</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Oleksandr Gimanov/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="902" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822596?width=1260&amp;height=902" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰东部的乌克兰士兵。美国官员承认反攻进展缓慢。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Oleksandr Ratushniak/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>一位欧洲高级官员表示，基辅的任务是一项艰巨的任务，他表示，他的政府几乎不指望乌克兰军队能够将俄罗斯军队驱逐出整个乌克兰东部或<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/blasts-hit-military-base-in-russian-occupied-crimea-c9c1ffc1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">夺回克里米亚</a>。他承认，虽然惊喜是有可能的，但可能性并不一定。</p><p>这位官员表示：“我们并不指望他们能够收复俄罗斯失去的所有领土，尤其是考虑到克里米亚，甚至是 2014 年顿巴斯失去的领土。”该官员是乌克兰的坚定支持者之一。</p><p> Another challenge facing the US and its allies are dwindling reserves of key weaponry, a shortfall Washington recently sought to partly address by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-send-cluster-munitions-to-bolster-ukraines-fight-against-dug-in-russians-d2dd292f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">supplying Kyiv with cluster munitions</a> .</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>美国应该向乌克兰提供多少支持？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Speaking to reporters last week at the Aspen Security Forum, UK Foreign Secretary James Cleverly said the US and the West must continue to supply as much and as quickly possible to Ukraine.</p><p> “人们说，‘是的，但你知道吗，我们不能让橱柜空着。你必须把它保存起来以备不时之需，”他说。 “我的意思是，今天是下雨天。”</p><p>华盛顿的一位西方外交官表示，美国可能不得不接受乌克兰战争不会很快结束的事实，盟友需要做好为基辅提供物资的准备，以应对持续数年的冲突。</p><p>这位外交官表示：“唯一真正的回应是工业动员，这将向乌克兰人和俄罗斯人传达一个明确的信息：乌克兰人将永远拥有充足的需求。”</p><p>问题是，如果攻势继续低于预期，美国及其盟友是否有决心继续支持，甚至扩大支持。乌克兰的首要愿望是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-close-to-approving-long-range-atacms-missiles-to-bolster-ukraines-fight-cc4e389c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国制造的 ATACMS</a>远程导弹和更快地采购 F-16 战斗机。</p><p>加拿大副总理克里斯蒂亚·弗里兰上周在阿斯本安全论坛上发表讲话，公开担心西方盟友坚持到底的能力。</p><p> “实际上，我对乌克兰最大的恐惧是我们，”她说。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Alan Cullison、William Mauldin 和 Sharon Weinberger 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Gordon Lubold ( <a href="mailto:gordon.lubold@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">gordon.lubold@wsj.com)</a> 、Michael R. Gordon ( <a href="mailto:michael.gordon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">michael.gordon@wsj.com</a> ) 和 Warren P. Strobel ( <a href="mailto:Warren.Strobel@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Warren.Strobel@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-stalled-offective-puts-biden-in-uneasy-political-position-6f686ab5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-stalled-offective-puts-biden-in-uneasy-political-position-6f686ab5<author><![CDATA[Gordon LuboldMichael R. GordonWarren P. Strobel]]></author><category> ukraine</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>National/Public Security</category><category> International Relations</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Risk News</category><category> Military Action</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>约翰·赫布斯特</category><category>托马斯·格雷厄姆</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>public security</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>risk news</category><category> military action </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Stock Market Shrugs Off Recession Signals as Rally Builds]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> S&amp;P 500 is trading near its highest level since April 2022 as hopes grow for a soft landing <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001080575"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822993?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> After a rally this year, the S&amp;P 500 has climbed about 27% from its recent bottom.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: BRENDAN MCDERMID/REUTERS </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001080575"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/karen-langley" itemprop="url" rel="author">Karen Langley</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 25 日中午 12:00（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/stock-market-shrugs-off-recession-signals-as-rally-builds-e775deee"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Stocks have <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-stocks-markets-dow-news-07-24-2023-7a164bcb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">floated higher</a> as Wall Street dials back its recession forecasts. Some investors aren&#39;t ready to call the all-clear.</p><p> They point to worrying economic signals, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/feds-stern-message-amplifies-worries-about-stock-valuations-11655243533?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">lofty equity valuations</a> and the possibility that the Federal Reserve continues raising interest rates or keeps them elevated longer than the market anticipates. The S&amp;P 500, meanwhile, has advanced 19% this year even as analysts expect 2023 corporate earnings to barely inch up.</p><p> “There&#39;s not a lot of leeway for bad news right now in equities,” said Mike Mullaney, director of global markets research at Boston Partners.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Will the Fed be able to tame inflation without a recession?为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Investors are all but certain that the central bank will raise interest rates by a quarter percentage point Wednesday. Their focus is on the future: any sign of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-fed-isnt-ready-to-declare-victory-on-inflation-e882b4d9?mod=economy_lead_story&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">whether Fed officials expect</a> to lift rates higher from there.</p><p> Not long ago, brutally hot inflation and the Fed&#39;s plans to fight it made the prognosis for markets and the economy <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/there-is-a-long-term-danger-lurking-in-financial-markets-e575491a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">appear bleak</a> .</p><p> Since the early 1950s, every episode of significant US disinflation, each of which was driven at least partly by Fed tightening, has been accompanied by recession, according to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DB" class="company-name">Deutsche Bank</a> research. That has been bad news for stocks: In recessions since the late 1940s, the S&amp;P 500 has fallen a median of 24%, according to the bank&#39;s research.</p><p> Last year the stock market seemed to be signaling such a contraction, with the S&amp;P 500 sliding 25% from its high in January 2022 to its low in October. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822916?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Many investors expected more of the same at the start of 2023. Instead, stocks roared higher out of the gate. The S&amp;P 500 emerged last month from its <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-06-08-2023/card/s-p-500-says-goodbye-to-its-longest-bear-market-since-the-1940s-vu6HsVabVKb5dcbg6qgI?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">longest bear market</a> since the 1940s and has now climbed 27% from its bottom. It is hovering near its highest levels since April 2022.</p><p> Inflation has cooled and the economy keeps motoring along. The jobs market remains robust, with the unemployment rate hitting a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/january-jobs-report-unemployment-rate-economy-growth-2023-11675374490" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">53-year low</a> earlier this year before ticking up just slightly. Americans have been spending more at retail businesses. Economists are raising estimates for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/economists-are-cutting-back-their-recession-expectations-74118938" target="_blank" class="icon none">gross domestic product</a> in the second and third quarters. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=DE0B91C0-D4B9-4619-AFE8-7EA4E62BC84B&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fstock-market-shrugs-off-recession-signals-as-rally-builds-e775deee&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The Federal Reserve is central to the US economy today, but its power has been built over decades. Its decisions can lower inflation or spark a recession. WSJ explains how the Fed was formed and the role it plays in the country. Photo Illustration: Annie Zhao<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“There&#39;s an actual chance here the Fed could stick the landing,” said Dryden Pence,</p> chief investment officer at Pence Capital Management.<p></p><p> Still, there are reasons for concern. The Conference Board said last week that its leading economic index fell for a 15th consecutive month, signaling slowing economic activity ahead. That is the index&#39;s longest streak of declines since a span from the spring of 2007 through early 2009. The US economy fell into a recession in December 2007 and didn&#39;t exit <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703989304575503691644231892?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">until June 2009</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822681?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> The bond market is flashing another warning sign. Normally, longer-term US Treasurys carry higher yields than shorter-term ones, paying investors for the risk that interest rates rise or inflation accelerates. When the longer-term yields are lower, it often suggests that investors think the Fed will need to cut rates to resuscitate the economy.</p><p> The yield on the benchmark 10-year US Treasury note has been lower than that of the 2-year Treasury for more than a year, the longest streak since a span ending in 1980, according to Dow Jones Market Data.</p><p> There have also been glimpses of weakening in the market for bank loans. Loan officers at US banks <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-05-08-2023/card/lending-standards-tightened-in-first-quarter-banks-say-Uw0mm1ue6lpajbeGSmar?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">told the Federal Reserve</a> earlier this year that they had tightened lending standards for households and businesses and also seen lower demand from borrowers. Tighter lending conditions can weigh on economic growth as firms pull back on investment and hiring and consumers have less money at their disposal. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822976?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Investors are watching for any sign that the Federal Reserve expects to lift rates after this month.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Graeme Sloan/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p></p> Hans Olsen, chief investment officer at Fiduciary Trust, said he finds the stock market&#39;s rally perplexing given the warning signs from various economic indicators. His firm sold US stocks in April and is holding more cash than usual to protect against a market downturn, he said.<p></p><p> “When you looked at that data set, you went, hold on here, this kind of looks like a classic slowdown in an economy that eventually slides into some form of contraction,” Olsen said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822847?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Such concerns come as the stock market is boasting rich valuations relative to history. The S&amp;P 500 traded late last week at 19.6 times its projected earnings over the next 12 months, up from 16.8 at the end of last year and above a 10-year average of 17.7, according to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/FDS" class="">FactSet</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span></p><p></p><p> Although there is no rule that valuations can&#39;t stay elevated, or climb even higher, some investors worry that the high price tag makes the market <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-ways-the-bull-market-makes-investors-nervous-2f0bf74c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">more vulnerable to a pullback</a> .</p><p> And while inflation has cooled notably, easing in June to its slowest pace in more than two years, it remains well above the Fed&#39;s 2% target. Central bank officials may not be satisfied without lifting rates again later this year or keeping them high for an extended period. And that could have unpredictable consequences.</p><p> “Everyone&#39;s sort of come to peace with a higher fed-funds rate,” said Katie Nixon, chief investment officer at Northern Trust Wealth Management. “I don&#39;t think we&#39;ve quite come to grips with what the implications of staying at that level for a prolonged period of time might mean for the economy and certainly for the markets.”</p><p> Write to Karen Langley at <a href="mailto:karen.langley@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">karen.langley@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/e0815ea6-ecc0-4136-bdae-5d2167589c29.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/stock-market-shrugs-off-recession-signals-as-rally-builds-e775deee</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/stock-market-shrugs-off-recession-signals-as-rally-builds-e775deee<author><![CDATA[Karen Langley]]></author><category>通货膨胀</category><category>华尔街日报金融市场</category><category>Financial Performance</category><category> Earnings</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Economic Performance/Indicators</category><category> Economic Growth/Recession</category><category> Economic News</category><category> Equity Markets</category><category> Commodity/Financial Market News</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>Inflation</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Dryden Pence</category><category> Hans Olsen</category><category> Mike Mullaney</category><category> Katie Nixon</category><category> financial performance</category><category> earnings</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>economic performance</category><category>指标</category><category>economic growth</category><category> recession</category><category> economic news</category><category> equity markets</category><category>商品</category><category>financial market news</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item></channel></rss>